5. a. Murgantiam. Murgantia was a town on the Symae- thus, and, according to Livy, on the coast. This descrip- tion, however, is said to be at variance with the notices of other writers. When Syracuse was besieged, Murgantia was held by a Roman garrison, but it was afterwards be- trayed to Himilco, and occupied by Hippocrates, who was watching the siege. It was recovered by the Romans, but revolted again after the departure of Marcellus from Sicily, ΒΛ). 211. Having been retaken by M. Cornelius the praetor, it was assigned to a body of Spaniards who had deserted to the Romans.
